Dasein half expected to see a maid in ruffled cap, apron with a bow at the back, long skirt and black stockings, sensible shoes -- or a portly banker type with tight vest and high collar, an expanse of gold chain at the waist.  
He felt out of place, out of style here.
\par 
\par The brass key worked smoothly in the door of two fifty-one; it let him into a room of high ceilings, one window looking down onto the parking area.  
Dasein turned on the light.  The switch controlled a tasseled floor lamp beside a curve-fronted teak dresser.  The amber light revealed a partly opened doorway into a tiled bathroom (the sound of water dripping 
there), a thick-legged desk-table with a single straight chair pushed against it.  The bed was narrow and high with a heavily carved headboard.
\par 
\par Dasein pushed down on the surface of the bed.  It felt soft.  He dropped his suitcase onto the bed, stared at it.  An edge of white fabric protruded from one end.  He opened the suitcase, studied the contents.  
Dasein knew himself for a prissy, meticulous packer.  The case now betrayed a subtle disarray.  Someone had opened it and searched it.  Well, it hadn't been locked.  He checked the contents -- nothing missing.
\par 
\par Why are they curious about me? he wondered.
\par 
\par He looked around for a telephone, found it, a standard French handset, on a shelf beside the desk.  As he moved, he caught sight of himself in the mirror above the dresser -- eyes wide, mouth in a straight line.  
Grim.  He shook his head, smiled.  The smile felt out of place.
\par 
\par Dasein sat down in the straight chair, put the phone to his ear.  There was a smell of disinfectant soap in the room -- and something like garlic.  After a moment, he jiggled the hook.
\par 
\par Presently, a woman's voice came on:  "This is the desk."
\par 
\par "I'd like to place a call to Berkeley," Dasein said.  He gave the number.  There was a moment's silence, then:  "Your room number, sir?"
\par 
\par "Two fifty-one."
\par 
\par "One moment, please."
\par 
\par He heard the sound of dialing, ringing.  Another operator came on the line.  Dasein listened with only half his attention as the call was placed.  The smell of garlic was quite strong.  He stared at the high old bed, his open suitcase.  
The bed appeared inviting, telling him how tired he was.  His chest ached.  He took a deep breath.
\par 
\par "Dr. Selador here."
\par 
\par Selador's India-cum-Oxford accent sounded familiar and close.  Dasein bent to the telephone, identi
fied himself, his mind caught suddenly by that feeling of intimate nearness linked to the knowledge of the actual distance, the humming wires reaching down almost half the length of the state.
\par 
\par "Gilbert, old fellow, you made it all right, I see."  Selador's voice was full of cheer.
\par 
\par "I'm at the Santaroga House, Doctor."
\par 
\par "I hear it's quite comfortable."
\par 
\par "Looks that way."  Through his buzzing tiredness, Dasein felt a sense of foolishness.  Why had he made this call?  Selador's sharp mind would probe for underlying meanings, motives.
\par 
\par "I presume you didn't call just to tell me you've arrived," Selador said.
\par 
\par "No . . . I . . ."  Dasein realized he couldn't express his own vague uneasiness, that it wouldn't make sense, this feeling of estrangement, the separation of Santarogans and Outsiders, the pricklings of warning fear.  
"I'd like you to look into the oil company dealings with this area," Dasein said.  "See if you can find out how they do business in the valley.  There's apparently an independent
 service station here.  I want to know who supplies the gas, oil, parts -- that sort of thing."
\par 
\par "Good point, Gilbert.  I'll put one of our . . ."  There was a sudden crackling, bapping sound on the line.  It stopped and there was dead silence.
\par 
\par "Dr. Selador?"
\par 
\par Silence.
\par 
\par Damn!  Dasein thought.  He jiggled the hook.  "Operator.  Operator!"
\par 
\par A masculine voice came on the line.  Dasein recognized the desk clerk's twang.  "Who's that creating all that commotion?" the clerk demanded.
\par 
\par "I was cut off on my call to Berkeley," Dasein said.  "Could you . . . "
\par 
\par "Line's out," the clerk snapped.
\par 
\par "Could I come down to the lobby and place the call from a pay phone?" Dasein asked.  As he asked it, the thought of walking that long distance down to the lobby repelled Dasein.  The feeling of tiredness was a weight on his chest.
\par 
\par "There's no line out of the valley right now," the clerk said.  "Call can't be placed."
\par 
\par Dasein passed a hand across his forehead.  His skin felt clammy and he wondered if he'd picked up a germ.  
The room around him seemed to expand and contract.  His mouth was dry and he had to swallow twice before asking:  "When do they expect to have the line restored?"
\par 
\par "How the hell do I know?" the clerk demanded.
\par 
\par Dasein took the receiver away from his ear, stared at it.  This was a very peculiar desk clerk . . . and a very peculiar room the way it wavered and slithered with its stench of garlic and its . . .
\par 
\par He grew aware of a faint hissing.
\par 
\par Dasein's gaze was drawn on a string of growing astonishment to an old-fashioned gaslight jet that jutted from the wall beside the hall door.
\par 
\par Stink of garlic?  Gas!
\par 
\par A yapping, barking voice yammered on the telephone.
\par 
\par Dasein looked down at the instrument in his hand.  How far away it seemed.  Through the window beyond the phone he could see the Inn sign:  Gold Rush Museum.  
Window equaled air.  Dasein found muscles that obeyed, lurched across the desk, fell, smashing the telephone through the window.
\par 
\par The yapping voice grew fainter.
\par 
\par Dasein felt his body stretched across the desk.  His head lay near the shattered window.  He could see the telephone cord stretching out the window.  There was cool air blowing on a distant forehead, a painful chill in his lungs.
\par 
\par They tried to kill me, he thought.  It was a wondering thought, full of amazement.  His mind focused on the two investigators who'd already died on this project -- accidents.  Simple, easily explained accidents . . . just like this one!
\par 
\par The air -- how cold it felt on his exposed skin.  His lungs burned with it.  There was a hammering pulse at his temple where it pressed against the desk surface.  The pulse went on and on and on . . .
\par 
\par A pounding on wood joined the pulse.  For a space, they beat in an insane syncopation.
\par 
\par "You in there!  Open up!"  How commanding, that voice.  Open up, Dasein thought.  That meant getting to one's feet, crossing the room, turning a door handle . . .
\par 
\par I'm helpless, he thought.  They could still kill me.
\par 
\par He heard metal rasp against metal.  The air blew stronger across his face.  Someone said:  "Gas!"
\par 
\par Hands grabbed Dasein's shoulders.  He was hauled back, half carried, half dragged out of the room.  The face of Marden, the red-haired patrol captain, swung across his vision.  He saw the cler
k:  pale, staring face, bald forehead glistening under yellow light.  There was a brown ceiling directly in front of Dasein.  He felt a rug, hard and rasping, beneath his back.
\par 
\par A twanging voice said:  "Who's going to pay for that window?"  Someone else said:  "I'll get Dr. Piaget."
\par 
\par Dasein's attention centered on Marden's mouth, a blurred object seen through layers of distortion.  There appeared to be anger lines at the corners of the mouth.  It turned toward the hovering pale face of the desk clerk, s
