\par 
\par "Don't you take that tone with me, Al Marden.  I've known you since . . ."
\par 
\par "I'm not interested in how long you've known me, Johnson.  How many rooms still have those gas jets?"
\par 
\par The clerk's voice came with an angry tone of hurt:  "Only this'n an' four upstairs.  Nobody in the other rooms."
\par 
\par "Get 'em out by tomorrow night," Marden said.
\par 
\par Hurrying footsteps interrupted the argument.  Dr. Piaget's round face blotted out Dasein's view of the ceiling.  The face wore a look of concern.  Fingers reached down, spread Dasein's eyelids.  Piaget said:  "Let's get him on a bed."
\par 
\par "Is he going to be all right?" the clerk asked.
\par 
\par "It's about time you asked," Marden said.
\par 
\par "We got him in time," Piaget said.  "Is that room across the hall empty?"
\par 
\par "He can have 260," the clerk said.  "Ill open it."
\par 
\par "You realize this is Jenny's fellow from the school you almost killed?" Marden asked, his voice receding as he moved away beside the clerk.
\par 
\par "Jenny's fellow?"  There was the sound of a key in a lock.  "But I thought . . ."
\par 
\par "Never mind what you thought!"
\par 
\par Piaget's face moved close to Dasein.  "Can you hear me, young fellow?" he asked.
\par 
\par Dasein drew in a painful breath, croaked, "Yes."
\par 
\par "You'll have quite a head, but you'll recover."
\par 
\par Piaget's face went away.  Hands picked Dasein up.  The ceiling moved.  There was another room around him:  like the first one -- tall ceiling, even the sound of dripping water.  He felt a bed beneath his back, hands beginning to undress him.  
Sudden nausea gripped him.  Dasein pushed the hands away.
\par 
\par Someone helped him to the bathroom where he was sick.  He felt better afterward -- weak, but with a clearer head, a better sense of control over his muscles.  He saw it was Piaget who'd helped him.
\par 
\par "Feel like getting back to bed now?" Piaget asked.
\par 
\par "Yes."
\par 
\par "I'll give you a good shot of iron to counteract the gas effect on your blood," Piaget said.  "You'll be all right."
\par 
\par "How'd that gas jet get turned on?" Dasein asked.  His voice came out a hoarse whisper.
\par 
\par "Johnson got mixed up fooling with the valves in the kitchen," Piaget said.  "Wouldn't have been any harm done if some idiot hadn't opened the jet in your room."
\par 
\par "I coulda sworn I had 'em all turned off."  That was the clerk's voice from somewhere beyond the bathroom door.
\par 
\par "They better be capped by tomorrow night," Marden said.
\par 
\par They sounded so reasonable, Dasein thought.  Marden appeared genuinely angry.  The look on Piaget's face could be nothing other than concern.
\par 
\par Could it have been a real accident? Dasein wondered.
\par 
\par He reminded himself then two men had died by accident in this valley while engaged in the investigation.
\par 
\par "All right," Piaget said.  "Al, you and Pim and the others can clear out now.  I'll get him to bed."
\par 
\par "Okay, Larry.  Clear out, all of you."  That was Marden.
\par 
\par "I'll get his bags from the other room."  That was a voice Dasein didn't recognize.
\par 
\par Presently, with Piaget's help, Dasein found himself in pajamas and in the bed.  He felt clearheaded, wide awake and lonely even with Piaget still in the room.
\par 
\par Among strangers, Dasein thought.
\par 
\par "Here, take this," Piaget said.  He pressed two pills into Dasein's mouth, forced a glass of water on him.  Dasein gulped, felt the pills rasp down his throat in a wash of water.
\par 
\par "What was that?" Dasein asked as he pushed the glass away.
\par 
\par "The iron and a sedative."
\par 
\par "I don't want to sleep.  The gas . . ."
\par 
\par "You didn't get enough gas to make that much difference.  Now, you rest easy."  Piaget patted his shoulder.  "Bed rest and fresh air are the best therapy you can get.  Someone'll look in on you from time to time tonight.  I'll check bac
k on you in the morning."
\par 
\par "Someone," Dasein said.  "A nurse?"
\par 
\par "Yes," Piaget said, his voice brusk.  "A nurse.  You'll be as safe here as in a hospital."
\par 
\par Dasein looked at the night beyond the room's window.  Why the feeling of danger now, then? he wondered.  Is it reaction?  He could feel the sedative blurring his senses, soothing him.  The sense of danger persisted.
\par 
\par "Jenny will be happy to know you're here," Piaget said.  He left the room, turning off the light, closing the door softly.
\par 
\par Dasein felt he had been smothered in darkness.  He fought down panic, restored himself to a semblance of calm.
\par 
\par Jenny . . . Jenny . . .
\par 
\par Marden's odd conversation with the clerk, Johnson, returned to him.  " . . . Jenny's fellow from the school . . ."
\par 
\par What had Johnson thought?  What was the thing Marden had cut short?
\par 
\par Dasein fought the sedative.  The drip-drip of water in the bathroom invaded his awareness.  The room was an alien cell.
\par 
\par Was it just an accident?
\par 
\par He remembered the fragmented confusion of the instant when he'd focused on that hissing gas jet.  Now, when the danger was past, he felt terror.
\par 
\par It couldn't have been an accident!
\par 
\par But why would Johnson want to kill him?
\par 
\par The disconnected telephone call haunted Dasein.  Was the line really down?  What would Selador do?  Selador knew the dangers here.
\par = -
\par Dasein felt the sedative pulling him down into sleep.  He tried to focus on the investigation.  It was such a fascinating project.  He could hear Selador explaining the facets that made the Santaroga Project such a glittering gem-
\par 
