\par "You go easy on that shoulder or I'll tell Uncle Larry," she said.  She kicked away from the walk, swam lazily out toward the float.
\par 
\par Dasein followed, making his way through dripping swimmers running up and down the walk.  It struck him as odd how this crowd saw him but didn't see him.  They made way for him, but never looked at him.  They shouted across him, but not to him.
\par 
\par He moved to the first boat in the line, untied its painter and prepared to get into it.  Jenny was swimming some fifty feet out, a slow, smooth crawl that took her diagonally away from the float.
\par 
\par Dasein stood up, moved to step into the boat.  As he stepped, something pushed him in the middle of the back.  His foot kicked the gunwale, thrusting the boat out into the water.  He saw he was going to fall into the lake, thought:
  Oh, damn!  I'll get my clothes all wet.  The stern of the boat was turning toward him and he thought of trying to reach for it, but his left foot on the dock slipped in a patch of wet wood.  Dasein found himself turning sideways without any control over
 his motion.
\par 
\par The edge of the boat, seen out of the corner of an eye, rushed toward him.  He tried to reach up, but that was the side of his bad shoulder.  His arm wouldn't move fast enough.
\par 
\par There was an explosion of blackness in his head.  Dasein felt himself sinking into an enveloping cold, soundless, all dark and inviting.
\par 
\par A part of his mind screamed:  Beauty!  Menace!
\par 
\par He thought that an odd combination.
\par 
\par There was a distant ache in his lungs and it was cold -- terrifyingly cold.  He felt pressure . . . and the cold . . . all distant and unimportant.
\par 
\par I'm drowning, he thought.
\par 
\par It was an unexciting thought -- something that concerned another person.
\par 
\par They won't see me . . . and I'll drown.
\par 
\par The cold grew more immediate -- wet.
\par 
\par Something turned him violently.
\par 
\par Still, everything remained remote -- all happening to that other being which he knew to be himself, but which could not concern him.
\par 
\par Jenny's voice broke on him like a thunderclap:  "Help me!  Please!  Someone help me!  Oh, God!  Won't someone help me?  I love him!  Please help me!"
\par 
\par He grew aware suddenly of other hands, other voices.
\par 
\par "All right, Jen.  We've got him."
\par 
\par "Please save him!"  Her voice carried a sobbing intensity.
\par 
\par Dasein felt himself draped across something hard that pressed into his abdomen.  Warmth gushed from his mouth.  There was a blinding, terrible pain in his chest.
\par 
\par Abruptly, he began to cough -- gasping, the pain tearing at his throat and bronchia.
\par 
\par "He swallowed a lot of water."  It was a man's voice, almost vacant of emotion.
\par 
\par Jenny's voice came pleading beside Dasein's ear:  "Is he breathing?  Please don't let anything happen to him."  Dasein felt wetness on his neck, and still Jenny's voice pleading there beside him:  "I love him.  Please save him."
\par 
\par That same unemotional male voice answered:  "We understand, Jenny."
\par 
\par And another voice, husky, feminine:  "There's only one thing to do, of course."
\par 
\par "We're doing it!"  Jenny screamed.  "Don't you understand?"
\par 
\par Even as hands picked Dasein up, began carrying him, Dasein wondered:  Doing what?
\par 
\par His coughing had subsided, but the pain in his chest remained.  It hurt when he breathed.
\par 
\par Presently, there was grass under his back.  Something warm and confining was wrapped around him.  It was an oddly womblike sensation.
\par 
\par Dasein opened his eyes, found himself staring up at Jenny, her dark hair framed by blue sky.  She managed a trembling smile.
\par 
\par "Oh, thank God," she whispered.
\par 
\par Hands lifted his shoulders.  Jenny's face went away.  A cup full of steaming brown liquid was pressed against his lips.  Dasein experienced the almost overpowering smell of Jaspers, felt hot coffee burn down his throat.
\par 
\par Immediately, a sense of warmth and well-being began to seep outward through his body.  The cup was pulled away, returned when he moved his mouth toward it.
\par 
\par Someone laughed, said something that Dasein couldn't quite catch.  It sounded like, "Take a full load."  But that didn't make sense and he rejected it.
\par 
\par The hands eased him gently back to the grass.  That vacant masculine voice said:  "Keep him warm and quiet for awhile.  He's okay."
\par 
\par Jenny's face returned.  Her hand stroked his head.
\par 
\par "Oh, darling," she said.  "I looked at the dock and you were gone.  I didn't see you fall, but I knew.  And no one was paying any attention.  It took me so long to get there.  Oh, your poor head.  Such a bruise."
\par 
\par Dasein felt the throbbing then as though her words had turned it on -- a pulsing ache at the temple and across his ear.  A blow like that -- shouldn't I have X-rays? he wondered.  How do they know I haven't a fractured skull . . . or concussion?
\par 
\par "Cal says the boat must've been tipping away from you as you hit it," Jenny said.  "I don't think you've broken anything."
\par 
\par Pain shot through him as she touched the bruise.
\par 
\par "It's just a bad bruise."
\par 
\par Just a bad bruise! he thought.  He was filled with abrupt anger at her.  How could they be so casual?
\par 
\par Still, that feeling of warmth spread out through him, and he thought:  Of course I'm all right.  I'm young, healthy.  I'll heal.  And I have Jenny to protect me.  She loves me.
\par 
\par Something about this train of thought struck him as profoundly wrong then.  He blinked.  As though that were the creative mechanism, his vision blurred, resolved in
to flashes of gemlike light, red, orange, yellow, brown, green, violet, blue light with offshooting crystal shards.
\par 
\par The light resolved into a membranous inward sensation, a perception of perception that reached out through his mind.  He saw then strong 
pulses of his own heart, the tender brain sheathing that rose and fell with the pulse, the damaged area -- just a bruise, skull intact.
\par 
\par Dasein grew aware then why the Santarogans showed so little concern for his injury.  They knew the injury through him.  If he were like them, he would tell them when he needed help.
\par 
\par Then why didn't they try to rescue me until Jenny came?  Dasein asked himself.  And the answer lay there to wonder at:  Because I didn't cry out for help in my thoughts!
\par 
\par "You shouldn't sleep now, I don't think," Jenny said.
\par 
\par She found his left hand, gripped it.  "Isn't there something about not sleeping after a head injury?"
\par 
\par Dasein stared up at her, seeing the dark wings of her hair disarrayed from rescuing him, the way her eyes see
med to touch him, so intense was her concentration.  There was dampness on her lashes and he felt that he might look behind her eyes and find the way to a magic land.
\par 
\par "I love you," he whispered.
\par 
\par She pressed a finger against his lips.  "I know."
\par 
\par I am a Santarogan now, Dasein thought.
\par 
\par He lay there rolling the thought in his mind, filled by this odd awareness that let him reach out to Jenny even when she released his hand and left him alone there on the grass.  There was nothing of telepathy in thi
s awareness.  It was more knowledge of mood in those around him.  It was a lake in which they all swam.  When one disturbed the water, the others knew it.
\par 
\par My God!  What this Jaspers could do for the world! Dasein thought.
\par 
\par But this thought sent roiling waves through the lake of mutual awareness.  There was storm in this thought.  It was dangerous.  Dasein recoiled from it.
\par 
\par He remembered then why he had come here and saw the conflict from a new perspective.  The people who'd sent him -- what did they want?  Proof, he thought.
\par 
\par He found he couldn't focus on what they wanted to prove.  It was all tied up with Jersey Hofstedder's car and the blunt Yankee insularity of these people.
\par 
\par Jenny's friends were noticing him now, Dasein saw.  They looked at h
im -- directly at him.  They spoke to him.  And when he felt he wanted to get up and go to the big fire they'd built against the evening chill, strong hands came without bidding and helped him.  Night fell.
\par 
\par Dasein found himself seated on a blanket besid
e Jenny.  Someone was playing a guitar in the darkness.  Moon colored half the lake, leaving a great black stone of night against one side.  Wind-wrinkled water lapped at the stone and he felt that if the blackness could only be moved it would blaze in li
ght to reveal fairyland.
\par 
\par Jenny snuggled against him, murmured:  "You're feeling better.  I know it."  He agreed with her silently.
\par 
\par Torches flamed down by the lake -- people securing the boats.  Someone handed him a sandwich redolent with Jaspers.  He 
ate, his attention on the torches and the fire -- the trees around them gleaming red, grotesque shadows lurching, dove wings of smoke against the moon.  Abruptly, Dasein secreted part of his sandwich in a pocket.
\par 
\par For no reason he could explain, Dasein r
emembered a time shortly after Jenny had left the school.  It had rained.  He remembered reaching out his window to feel the rain, seeing the wet sparkle of the lawn beneath a window, like a broken necklace scattered there.
\par 
\par Abruptly, the wind across the lake shifted, stung his eyes with smoke.  He swallowed a mouthful of the smoke and it brought him to an intense awareness of the here and now, Jenny beside him . . . waiting.
\par 
\par As he thought about her, she reached up, pulled his lips down on hers.  It was a long kiss, full of guitar music, remembered rain and the taste of smoke.
\par 
\par How can I ever explain this?  Dasein wondered.  Selador would think me mad.
\par 
\par Jenny stirred against him at this thought, stroked his neck.
\par 
\par "Let's get married soon," she whispered.
\par 
\par Why not?  Dasein asked himself.  I'm a Santarogan now.
\par 
\par But this thought brought a surge of fear that tightened his chest and made Jenny shiver.  She pulled away, stared at him with worry in her eyes.
\par 
\par "Everything will be all right," she whispered.  "You'll see."
\par 
\par The worry remained in her voice, though.  And Dasein sensed menace in the night.  The guitarist struck a sour note, fell silent.
\par 
\par Dasein saw that moonlight had moved into the black area of the lake . . . and it revealed no fairyland -- only more lake, more trees.
\par 
\par The night was definitely cold now.
\par 
\par Once more, Jenny pressed her lips to his.
\par 
\par Dasein knew he still loved her.  It was a real thing to which he could cling.  But there was no more magic in this night.  He felt that he had skirted madness and the thing had left its taint on him.
\par 
\par When she pulled away, he whispered:  "I want to marry you, Jenny.  I love you . . . but . . . I need time.  I need . . ."
\par 
\par "I know, darling," she said.  She stroked his cheek.  "Take all the time you need."
\par 
\par Her voice carried a withdrawing note compounded as she pulled back.  Dasein felt the night's coldness then, the stillness of their companions.
\par 
\par Abruptly, there was a stirring in the people around them.  They began moving toward the truck.
\par 
\par "It's time to go back," Jenny said.
\par 
\par Back where? Dasein asked himself.
\par 
\par Jenny stood up, helped him to his feet.  He stumbled in a brief spasm of dizziness.  Jenny steadied him.
\par 
\par "Do you want Uncle Larry to look at your head tonight?" she asked.
\par 
\par Piaget, Dasein thought.  That was the back at which he was aimed.  Piaget.  They would continue their trade of truths.  The Jaspers change was forcing it.
\par 
\par I'll see him in the morning, Dasein said.
\par 
\par "Not tonight?"
\par 
\par In my own sweet time, Dasein thought.  And he said:  "Not tonight."
\par 
\par The answer seemed to trouble Jenny.  She sat barely touching him on the ride back to town.
\par 
