\par Chapter 7
\par 
\par 
\par Daylight found Dasein staring up at the camper's metal ceiling with a sense of disorientation.  He recognized the ceiling, but couldn't locate it in space.  His head and shoulder throbbed.  Ceiling . . . familiar ceiling.
\par 
\par A car horn honked.  It brought him to the present and awareness.  He threw off the twisted folds of his sleeping bag, climbed out into a gray, overcast day.  His chin felt rough and stubbly.  There was a sour taste in his mouth.
\par 
\par Two passing schoolboys stared at him, whispering.
\par 
\par I must look a sight, Dasein thought.  He looked down at his clothes.  They were twisted and wrinkled as though he had gone swimming in them and then slept in them until they dried.  Dasein smiled to himself, thinking that was exactly what had happened.

\par 
\par He climbed into the cab, turned around and found the main street, drove down it until he saw the Post Office sign over the porch of a general store.
\par 
\par The postmaster had to finish selling candy to a girl before he could come around behind his caged counter to weigh Dasein's package and letter.  The man was tall, pale with thinning black hair, dartin
g, wary blue eyes.  He sniffed once at Dasein, said:  "That'll be eighty-four for the package and five for the letter."
\par 
\par Dasein pushed a dollar bill under the cage.
\par 
\par The man made change, looked once more at the package.  "What's in the package, mister?"
\par 
\par "Specimens for analysis at our laboratory," Dasein said.
\par 
\par "Oh."
\par 
\par The man didn't appear curious about specimens of what.  "Any return address?" he asked.
\par 
\par "Dr. Gilbert Dasein, general delivery, Santaroga," he said.
\par 
\par "Dasein," the man said with sudden interest.  "Dasein . . . seems I got a package for a Dasein.  Just a minute."
\par 
\par He disappeared into the back, returned in a moment with a box about a foot square wrapped neatly and tied with heavy twine.  Even from a distance, Dasein recognized Selador's precise script on the address.
\par 
\par Selador writing me here? Dasein wondered.
\par 
\par The air of conspiracy in this gave Dasein the abrupt sensation of being completely transparent to Selador.  The man could send a package here and know it would be picked 
up.  Immediately, Dasein told himself this was the simplest thing to figure -- given the Santaroga Post Office situation as he'd described it to Selador.
\par 
\par There remained, though, the feeling he was a pawn and his every move was known to the masters of the game.
\par 
\par "Let's see your identification," the postmaster said.
\par 
\par Dasein showed it.
\par 
\par "Sign here," the man said.
\par 
\par Dasein signed, took the package.  It felt heavy.
\par 
\par "Funny thing you Santarogans using my Post Office," the postmaster said.  "Something wrong with your own?"
\par 
\par Santarogans . . . plural, Dasein thought.  He said:  "Is some other . . . Santarogan using your Post Office?"
\par 
\par "Well -- used to be," the man said.  "Negro fellow over there . . . Burdeaux, as I recollect.  He used to send some mail from here.  Got a package here once from Louisiana.  Long time ago that was."
\par 
\par "Oh, yes," Dasein said, not knowing how else to acknowledge this information.
\par 
\par "Haven't seen Burdeaux in quite a spell," the postmaster mused.  "Nice fellow.  Hope he's all right."
\par 
\par "Quite all right," Dasein said.  "Well -- thank you."  He took his package, went out to the truck.
\par 
\par With a feeling of caution he couldn't explain, Dasein left the package unopened on the seat beside him while he drove east on the road to Santaroga until he found a shady spot in which to pull off.
\par 
\par The box contained a .32 caliber automatic pistol with an extra clip and box of cartridges.  Wired to the trigger guard was a note from Selador:  "Gilbert --  This has been gathering dust in my bu
reau drawer for many years and I'm probably an old woman for sending it to you, but here it is.  I think I'm sending it in the hope you won't have to use it.  The situation you describe, however, has filled me with the oddest sensations of disquiet that I
 can remember.  I hope you're being extremely cautious."
\par 
\par On the reverse side of the note was a scrawled postscript:  "No news yet on the investigations you requested.  These things move slowly.  You give me hope, though, that we'll get the goods on these people."  It was signed:  "S."
\par 
\par Dasein hefted the automatic, fought down an impulse to heave it out the window.  The thing embodied ultimate menace.  What had he said to prompt Selador to send it?  Or was this part of some obscure motivational gambit Selador was setting up?
\par 
\par Could it be a reminder of duty?  His bruised head ached with thought.
\par 
\par A line in Selador's note came back to him and he reread it:  ". . . get the goods on these people."
\par 
\par Is that what I'm supposed to do? Dasein wondered.  Am I to set them up for prosecution?
\par 
\par He remembered Marden alluding to the reasons an investigator had been sent.
\par 
\par Dasein swallowed.  Selador's line, read once more, looked like a slip.  Had the good doctor tipped his hand?  Sending a gun wasn't like the man.  In fact, Dasein realized if he'd been asked, he would've said Selador wasn't even the type to own a gun.

\par 
\par What to do with the damn' thing now that he had it?
\par 
\par Dasein checked it, found the clip full, no cartridge in the chamber.  He resisted the impulse to shove it in the glove compartment and forget it.  If the truck were searched. . . .
\par 
\par Damn Selador!
\par 
\par Feeling foolish as he did it, Dasein slipped the gun into a hip pocket, pulled his coat over it.  He'd settle with Selador later.  Right now there was Piaget . . . and Piaget had some answers to give.
