\par Chapter 8
\par 
\par 
\par Piaget was in his office with a patient when Dasein arrived.  The gaunt, gray Sarah opened the door, allowed he could wait in the living room.  With a grudging show of hospitality, she added that she would bring him some coffee if he wanted it.
\par 
\par With a stomach-gripping pang, Dasein realized he was ravenous with hunger.  He wondered if he could mention this fact.
\par 
\par As though she'd read his mind, Sarah said.  "I'll bet you haven't eaten breakfast."  She looked him up and down.  "You look like you'd slept in those clothes.  You doctors are all alike.  Never care how you look."
\par 
\par "As a matter of fact, I haven't eaten," Dasein said.
\par 
\par "You're going to lead Jenny some life," she said.  But she softened her words with a smile.
\par 
\par Dasein stared in wonder at a double, whiteboned row of false teeth in the wrinkled face.
\par 
\par "Got a leftover apple roll and some Jaspers cream," Sarah said.  "Bet you'd like that."
\par 
