\par 
\par "Dasein . . . Gilbert Dasein," he said.  And he thought:  So this is how they take care of their own.
\par 
\par "Jenny's fellow!" the woman said.  "Well, now."
\par 
\par Dasein looked at the boy.  Petey.  He appeared to be no more than twelve, almost as tall as the woman.  His face when the flashlight beam brushed it was a carbon copy of the man's.  No denying parenthood there.
\par 
\par "Turn the light over here, Bill," the woman said.  She spoke carefully and distinctly as one might to a very young child.  "Over here, hon."
\par 
\par "Over there, Pop."  The boy directed the man's uncertain hand.
\par 
\par "That's it, love," the woman said.  "I think I got the gigging hook caught in my coat."  She fussed with a length of line at her side.
\par 
\par "Hunh," the man said.
\par 
\par Dasein stared at him with a cold feeling of horror.  He could see himself there, Jenny "taking care" of him, their children helping.
\par 
\par "There," the woman said, pulling the line free and attaching it to the gigging pole.  "Turn the light down toward the ground now, Bill.  Toward the ground, hon."
\par 
\par "Down this way, Pop," the boy said, helping.
\par 
\par "That's a love," the woman said.  She reached out, patted the man's cheek.
\par 
\par Dasein felt something obscene in the gesture, wanted to turn away, couldn't.
\par 
\par "He's real good, Bill is," the woman said.
\par 
\par The boy began playing with his bow, drawing it, releasing it.
\par 
\par "What you doing out here, Dr. Dasein?" the woman asked.
\par 
\par "I . . . wanted to be . . . alone for awhile."  He forced himself to look at her.
\par 
\par "Well, this is a place to be alone all right," she said.  "You feel all right?  No . . . gutters . . . or anything?"
\par 
\par "Quite all right," Dasein said.  He shuddered.
\par 
\par The boy had knocked an arrow into the bow, was waving it about.
\par 
\par "I'm Mabel Jorick," the woman said.  "This is Bill, my husband; our son, Petey.  Petey's been . . . you know, with Doc Piaget.  Just got his bill of health."
\par 
\par "I passed," the boy said.
\par 
\par "Indeed you did, love."  She looked at Dasein.  "He's going outside to college next year."
\par 
\par "Isn't he kind of young?"  Dasein asked.  "Fifteen," she said.  "Hunh," the man said.
\par 
\par The boy had drawn the bow to its full arc, Dasein saw.  The arrow tip glittered in the light from the flash.
\par 
\par Up, down . . . right, left the arrow pointed.
\par 
\par Dasein moved uneasily as the tip traversed his chest -- across, back.  Sweat started on his forehead.  He felt menace in the boy.
\par 
\par Instinctively, Dasein moved to put the man between himself and Petey, but Jorick moved back, stared off toward the highway.
\par 
\par "I think he hears the car," the woman said.  "My brother, Jim, coming to pick us up."  She shook her head wonderingly.  "He has awful good hearing, Bill has."
\par 
\par Dasein felt a crisis rushing upon him, dropped to his hands and knees.  As he fell, he heard the bow twang, felt the wind of an arrow brush the back of his neck, heard it slam into the side of the camper.
\par 
\par "Petey!" the woman shouted.  She snatched the bow from him.  "What're you doing?"
\par 
\par "It slipped, Ma."
\par 
\par Dasein climbed to his feet studying these people narrowly.
\par 
\par "Hunh," the man said.
\par 
\par The mother turned toward Dasein, the bow in her hand.
\par 
\par "He tried to kill me," Dasein whispered.
\par 
\par "It was just an accident!" the boy protested.
\par 
\par The man lifted the flashlight, a menacing gesture.
\par 
\par Without looking at him, the woman said:  "Point it toward the ground, hon."  She pushed the light down, stared at Dasein.  "You don't think . . ."
\par 
\par "It was an accident," the boy said.
\par 
\par Dasein looked at the arrow.  It had penetrated halfway through the camper's wall on a level with his chest.  He tried to swallow in
 a dry throat.  If he hadn't ducked at just that instant . . .  An accident.  A regrettable accident.  The boy was playing with a bow and arrow.  It slipped.
\par 
\par Death by misadventure.
\par 
\par What warned me? Dasein wondered.
\par 
\par He knew the answer.  It lay there in his mind, clearly readable.  He had come to recognize the Santaroga pattern of menace.  The means might differ, but the pattern carried a sameness -- something lethal in an apparently innocent context.
\par 
\par "It was just an accident," the woman whispered.  "Petey wouldn't harm a fly."
\par 
\par She didn't believe it, Dasein saw.
\par 
\par And that was another thing.  He was still connected by a tenuous thread to the Jaspers oneness.  The warning message along that line was unmistakable.  She'd received it, too.
\par 
\par "Wouldn't he?" Dasein asked.  He looked once more at the arrow protruding from the camper.
\par 
\par The woman turned, grabbed her son's shoulder in one hand, shook the bow at him.  "You want to go back?" she demanded.  "Is that it?"
\par 
\par "Hunh," the man said.  He shuffled his feet uneasily.
\par 
\par "It was an accident," the boy said.  He obviously was near tears.
\par 
\par The woman turned a pleading look on Dasein.  "You wouldn't say anything to Doctor Larry, would you?"
\par 
\par "Say anything?"  Dasein stared at her stupidly.
\par 
\par "He might . . . you know, misunderstand."
\par 
\par Dasein shook his head.  What was she talking about?
\par 
\par "It's so hard," the woman said.  "After Bill, I mean.  You know how it is over there."  She gestured vaguely with her head.  "The way they keep such a close watch
