\par 
\par An accident . . . another bloody accident.
\par 
\par He kicked the fallen dish aside, dragged the dog out of the way, got behind the wheel of his camper.  The Ford's engine was a dismal, throbbing mess after Jersey's car.  He maneuvered it gently out to the highway, turned toward town.
\par 
\par Accident, he thought.
\par 
\par A pattern was emerging, but he found it difficult to accept.  There was a Holmesian flavor to his thought -- ". . . when you have eliminated the impossible, whatever remains, however improbable, must be the truth."
\par 
\par Jenny had screamed:  "Stay away from me.  I love you."
\par 
\par That was consistent.  She did love him.  Therefore, he had to stay away from her.
\par 
\par For the time being.
\par 
\par The road forked and he turned right, following the direction by a sign labeled:  "Greenhouses."
\par 
\par There was a bridge over the river -- an old-fashioned bridge that crowned in the middle . . . heavy planks rattling under the wheels.  The river foamed and bunched itself over the shell-backs of smooth stones under the bridge.
\par 
\par Dasein slowed the truck at the far side, taken suddenly by a warning sense of caution which he had learned to trust.
\par 
\par The road followed the river's right bank.  He paced the current, glanced upstream toward the bridge, found it hidden by a stand of willows:
\par 
\par It came over Dasein that there was something sliding and treacherous about the river.  He thought of a liquid snake, venomous, full of evil energy.  It contained a concentration of malevolence as it slip
ped down the rapids beside the road.  And the sound -- it laughed at him.
\par 
\par Dasein drew a sigh of relief when the road turned away from the river, wound over two low hills and down into a shallow valley.  He glimpsed the glass through trees.  It was an expanse of glistening green and covered a much larger area than he'd expected.

\par 
\par The road ended at a paved parking lot in front of a long stone building.  More stone buildings -- tile roofs, curtained windows -- stepped in ranks up the hill beside the greenhouses.
\par 
\par A great many cars waited in the parking lot, a fact Dasein found curious -- at least a hundred cars.
\par 
\par And there were people -- men walking between the greenhouses, white-coated figures behind the glass, briskly striding women coming and going.
\par 
\par Dasein drove down the line of cars looking for a place to park.  He found a slot beyond the end of the long stone building, pulled in to a stop and stared around.  Chanting.
\par 
\par Dasein turned toward the sound; it came from the ranks of buildings beyond 
the greenhouses.  A troop of children came marching into view down a path between the buildings.  They carried baskets.  Three adults accompanied them.  They counted a marching cadence.  The troop wound out of sight down into the greenhouse level.
\par 
\par A tight feeling gripped Dasein's chest.
\par 
\par Footsteps sounded on his left.  Dasein turned to find Piaget striding down the line of cars toward him.  The doctor's bulky figure was accented by a long white smock.  He was hatless, his hair wind mussed.
\par 
\par Piaget turned into the slot beside Dasein, stopped to stand looking in the truck's open window.
\par 
\par "Well," he said.  "Jenny said there'd be an arriving."
\par 
\par Dasein shook his head.  There was almost meaning in Piaget's words, but the sense eluded him.  He wet his lips with his tongue.  "What?"
\par 
\par Piaget scowled.  "Jenny knows rapport.  She said you'd probably show up here."  His voice sounded suddenly full of effort.
\par 
\par An arriving, Dasein thought.
\par 
\par It was a label for an event, a statement withholding judgment.  He studied Piaget's wide, bland face.
\par 
\par "I saw children," Dasein said.
\par 
\par "What did you expect?"
\par 
\par Dasein shrugged.  "Are you going to run me off?"
\par 
\par "Al Marden says the ones that run get the fever," Piaget said.  "The ones that watch get the benefit."
\par 
\par "Count me among the watchers," Dasein said.
\par 
\par Piaget grinned, opened the truck door.  "Come."
\par 
\par Dasein remembered the river, hesitated.  He thought of the torn carpet in the Inn's hallway, the open gas jet, the lake, the arrow . . . the paint bleach.  He thought of Jenny running away from him -- "Stay away from me!  I love you."
\par 
\par "Come along," Piaget said.
\par 
\par Still hesitating, Dasein said:  "Why're the children kept here?"
\par 
\par "We must push back at the surface of childhood," Piaget said.  "It's a brutal, animate thing.  But there's food growing."  He gestured at the expanse of greenhouses.  "There's educating.  There's useful energy.  Waste not; want not."
\par 
\par Again, Dasein shook his head.  Almost-meaning.
\par 
\par Push back at the surface of childhood?
\par 
\par It was like schizophrenic talk and he recalled the incident in the Blue Ewe, the haunting conversation of the young couple.
\par 
\par How could one hear a sunset?
\par 
\par "You . . . you're not speaking English," Dasein complained.
\par 
\par "I'm speaking," Piaget said.
\par 
\par "But . . ."
\par 
\par "Jenny says you'll be an understander."  Piaget scratched his cheek, a pensive look on his face.  "You have the training, Dasein."  Again, his voice took on that leaden effort.  "Where's your Weltanschauung?  You do have a world view?  The whole i
s greater than the sum of its parts.  What is it?"
\par 
\par Piaget's arm swept out to include the greenhouse complex and the entire valley, the world and the universe beyond.
\par 
\par Dasein's mouth felt dry.  The man was insane.
\par 
\par "You contain the Jaspers experience," Piaget said.  "Digest it.  Jenny says you can do it.  Reality shoots through her words."
\par 
\par The tight sensation was a pain in Dasein's chest.  Thoughts tumbled through his mind without order or sense.
\par 
\par In a heavy voice, Piaget said:  "For approximately one in five hundred, the Jaspers cannot . . ."  He spread his arms, palms up.  "You are not one of those few.  I stake a reputation on it.  You will be an opening person."
\par 
\par Dasein looked at the stone building, the hurrying people.  All that action and purpose.  He sensed it all might be like the dance of bees -- motions designed to show him a direction.  The direction escaped him.
\par 
\par "I will try to put it in the words of outside," Piaget said.  "Perhaps then . . ."  He shrugged, leaned against the side 
