\par 
\par "You won't come with me," he said.  "I'll go with you."
\par 
\par "You'll go with me?"
\par 
\par "To my house; to the clinic."  He turned, studied Dasein.  "I love my niece, you understand?  I'll not have her hurt if I can prevent it."
\par 
\par "If I refuse?"
\par 
\par "Ahh, Gilbert, you would make the angels weep.  We don't want weeping, do we?  We don't want Jenny's tears.  Aren't you concerned about her?"
\par 
\par "I've some anxiety about . . ."
\par 
\par "When anxiety enters, inquiry stops.  You have a hard head, Gilbert.  A hard head makes a sore back.  Let us go to the clinic."
\par 
\par "What kind of death trap have you set up there?"
\par 
\par Piaget glared at him in outrage.  "Death trap?"
\par 
\par Holding as reasonable a tone as he could manage, Dasein said:  "You're trying to kill me.  Don't deny it.  I've . . ."
\par 
\par "I'm disgusted with you, Gilbert.  When have we tried to kill you?"
\par 
\par Dasein took a deep breath, held up his right hand, enumerated the accidents, dropping a finger for each one until his hand was clenched into a fist.  He had left out only the incident with Petey Jorick . . . and that because of a promise.
\par 
\par "Accidents!" Piaget said.
\par 
\par "As we both know," Dasein said, "there are very few real accidents in this world.  Most of what we call accidents are unconscious violence.  You say you've opened your mind.  Use it."
\par 
\par "Pah!  Your thoughts are like muddy water!"
\par 
\par "Let the muddy water stand and it becomes clear," Dasein said.
\par 
\par "You can't be serious."  He glared at Dasein.  "But I see that you are."  He closed his eyes momentarily, opened them.  "Well, would you believe Jenny?"
\par 
\par Stay away from me!  I love you! Dasein thought.
\par 
\par "Let's go to your clinic," Dasein said.  He started the truck, backed out of the parking lot and headed toward town.
\par 
\par "Trying to kill you," Piaget muttered.  He stared out at the landscape rushing past them.
\par 
\par Dasein drove in silence . . . thinking, thinking, thinking
.  The instant he headed toward Jenny, the old fantasies gripped him.  Jenny and her valley!  The place had enveloped him in its aura -- crazy, crazy, crazy!  But the pattern was emerging.  It was going together with its own Santaroga kind of logic.

\par 
\par "So not everyone can take your . . . power medicine?"  Dasein asked.  "What happens to the ones who fail?"
\par 
\par "We take care of our own," Piaget growled.  "That's why I keep hoping you'll stay."
\par 
\par "Jenny's a trained psychologist.  Why don't you use her?"
\par 
\par "She does her tour of duty."
\par 
\par "I'm going to ask Jenny to leave with me," Dasein said.  "You know that, don't you?"
\par 
\par Piaget sniffed.
\par 
\par "She can break away from your . . . Jaspers," Dasein said.  "Men go into the service from here.  They must . . ."
\par 
\par "They always come home when it's over," Piaget said.  "That's in your notes.  Don't you realize how unhappy they are out there?"  He turned toward Dasein.  "Is that the choice you'd offer Jenny?"
\par 
\par "They can't be all that unhappy about leaving," Dasein said.  "Otherwise you clever people would've found another solution."
\par 
\par "Hmmph!" Piaget snorted.  "You didn't even do your homework for the people who hired you."  He sighed.  "I'll tell you, Gilbert.  The draft rejects most of our young men -- severe allerg
y reaction to a diet which doesn't include periodic administration of Jaspers.  They can only get that here.  The approximately six percent of our young people who go out do so as a duty to the valley.  We don't want to call down the federal wrath on us. 
 We have a political accommodation with the state, but we're not large enough to apply the same technique nationally."
\par 
\par They've already decided about me, Dasein thought.  They don't care what they tell me.
\par 
\par The realization brought a tight sensation of fear in the pit of his stomach.
\par 
\par He rounded a corner and came parallel with the river.  Ahead stood the clump of willows and the long, down-sweeping curve to the bridge.  Dasein recalled his projection of evil onto the river, stepped on the throttle to ge
t this place behind him.  The truck entered the curve.  The road was banked nicely.  The bridge came into view.  There was a yellow truck parked off the road at the far side, men standing behind it drinking out of metal cups.
\par 
\par "Look out!" Piaget shouted.
\par 
\par In that instant, Dasein saw the reason for the truck -- a gaping hole in the center of the bridge where the planks had been removed.  That was a county work crew and they'd opened at least a ten foot hole in the bridge.
\par 
\par The truck sped some forty feet during the moment it took Dasein to realize his peril.
\par 
\par Now, he could see a two-by-four stretched across each end of the bridge, yellow warning flags tied at their centers.
\par 
\par Dasein gripped the steering wheel.  His mind shifted into a speed of computation he had never before experienced.  The effect was to slow the external passage of time.  The truck seemed to come almost to a stop while he reviewed the possibilities --

\par 
\par Hit the brakes?
\par 
\par No.  Brakes and tires were old.  At this speed, the truck would skid onto the bridge and into the hole.
\par 
\par Swerve off the road?
\par 
\par No.  The river waited on both sides -- a deep cut in the earth to swallow them.
\par 
\par Aim for a bridge abutment to stop the truck?  Not at this speed and without seat belts.  Hit the throt
tle to increase speed?  That was a possibility.  There was the temporary barrier to break through, but that was only a two-by-four.  The bridge rose in a slight arc up and over the river.  The hole had been opened in the center.  Given enough speed, the t
ruck could leap the hole.
\par 
\par Dasein jammed the throttle to the floorboards.  The old truck leaped ahead.  There came a sharp cracking sound as they smashed through the barrier.  Planks clattered beneath the wheels.  There came a breathless instant of flying
, a spring-crushing lurch as they landed across the hole, the "crack" of the far barrier.
\par 
\par He hit the brakes, came to a screeching stop opposite the workmen.  Time resumed its normal pace as Dasein stared out at the crew -- five men, faces pale, mouths agape.
\par 
\par "For the love of heaven!" Piaget gasped.  "Do you always take chances like that?"
\par 
\par "Was there any other way to get us out of that mess?" Dasein asked.  He lifted his right hand, stared at it.  The hand was trembling.
\par 
\par Piaget reflected a moment, then:  "You took what was probably the only way out . . . but if you hadn't been driving so damn' fast on a blind . . ."
\par 
\par "I will make you a bet," Dasein said.  "I'll bet the work on that bridge wasn't necessary, that it was either a mistake or some sort of make-work."
\par 
\par Dasein reached for his door handle, had to grope twice to get it in his hand, then found it took a conscious surge of effort to open the door.  He stepped out, found his knees rubbery.  He stood a moment, took several deep breaths, the
n moved around to the front of the truck.
\par 
\par Both headlights were smashed and there was a deep dent stretching across both fenders and the grill.
\par 
\par Dasein turned his attention to the workmen.  One, a stocky, dark-haired man in a plaid shirt and dungarees stood a step ahead of the others.  Dasein focused on the man, said:  "Why wasn't there a warning sign back there around the corner?"
\par 
\par "Good God, man!" the fellow said.  His face reddened.  "Nobody comes down that road this time of day."
\par 
\par Dasein walked 
down the road toward a pile of planks, dirt and oil on them testifying that they'd been taken from the bridge.  They looked to be three-by-twelve redwood.  He lifted the end of one, turned it over-no cracks or checks.  It gave off the sharp sound of an un
broken board when he dropped it back to the pile.
\par 
\par He turned to see the workman he'd addressed approaching.  Piaget was several paces behind the man.
\par 
\par "When did you get the order to do this work?" Dasein asked.
\par 
\par "Huh?"  The man stopped, stared at Dasein with a puzzled frown.
\par 
\par "When did you get orders to repair this bridge?" Dasein asked.
\par 
\par "Well . . . we decided to come up here about an hour ago.  What the hell difference does it make?  You've smashed the . . ."
\par 
