\par 
\par Piaget climbed in beside him.  The truck rattled as he closed his door.  "Will it still run?"  he asked.
\par 
\par "Accident!" Dasein said.
\par 
\par Piaget remained silent.
\par 
\par Dasein put the truck in gear, eased it up to a steady thirty-five miles an hour.  The rear-view mirror showed him the crew already at work on the bridge, one of their number with a warning flag trudging back around the blind comer.
\par 
\par "Now, they send out a flagman," Dasein said.
\par 
\par A corner cut off the view in the mirror.  Dasein concentrated on driving.  The truck had developed new rattles and a front-end shimmy.
\par 
\par "They have to be accidents," Piaget said.  "There's no other explanation."
\par 
\par A stop sign came into view ahead.  Dasein stopped for the main highway.  It was empty of traffic.  He turned right toward town.  Piaget's protestations deserved no answer, he thought, and he gave no answer.
\par 
\par They entered the outskirts of town.  There was Scheler's station on the left.  Dasein pulled in behind the station, drove back to the large shed-roofed metal building labeled "Garage."
\par 
\par "What're you doing here?" Piaget asked.  "This machine isn't worth . . ."
\par 
