\par 
\par If I hadn't . . .  He aborted the thought.  If I hadn't what?  That accident was meant for me.
\par 
\par "It's all right, Harry," Piaget said.  "We understand."
\par 
\par "Thanks, Doc."  He looked at Piaget with relie
f.  "Dad said to tell you . . . the car, Dr. Dasein's truck . . . The new headlights are in it.  That's all we can do.  The steering . . .  You'll just have to drive slow unless you replace the whole front end."
\par 
\par "Already?" Dasein asked.
\par 
\par "It doesn't take long to put in headlights, sir."
\par 
\par Dasein looked from the youth to Piaget.  The doctor returned his stare with an expression that said as clearly as words:  "They want your truck out of there.  It's a reminder . . ."
\par 
\par Dasein nodded.  Yes.  The truck would remind them of the tragedy.  This was logical.  Without a word, he set off for the garage.
\par 
\par Piaget sped up, matched his pace to Dasein's.
\par 
\par "Gilbert," he said, "I must insist you come over to the house.  Jenny can . . ."
\par 
\par "Insist?"
\par 
\par "You're being very pig-headed, Gilbert."
\par 
\par Dasein put down a surge of anger, said:  "I don't want to hurt Jenny any more than you do.  That's why I'm going to direct my own steps.  I don't really want you to know what I'm going to do next.  I don't want any of you
 waiting there in my path with one of your . . . accidents."
\par 
\par "Gilbert, you must put that idea out of your mind!  None of us want to hurt you."
\par 
\par They were on the parking area between the station and the garage now.  Dasein stared at the gaping door to 
the garage, overcome suddenly by the sensation that the door was a mouth with deadly teeth ready to clamp down on him.  The door yawned there to swallow him.
\par 
\par Dasein hesitated, slowed, stopped.
\par 
\par "What is it now?" Piaget asked.
\par 
\par "Your truck's just inside," Harry Scheler said.  "You can drive it and . . ."
\par 
\par "What about the bill?" Dasein asked, stalling for time.
\par 
\par "I'll take care of that," Piaget said.  "Go get your truck while I'm settling up.  Then we'll go to . . ."
\par 
\par "I want the truck driven out here for me," Dasein said.  He moved to one side, out of the path of anything that might come spewing from that mouth-door.
\par 
\par "I can understand your reluctance to go back in there," Piaget said, "but really . . ."
\par 
\par "You drive it out for me, Harry," Dasein said.
\par 
\par The youth stared at Dasein with an oddly trapped look.  "Well, I have some . . ."
\par 
\par "Drive the damn' car out for him!" Piaget ordered.  "This is nonsense!"
\par 
\par "Sir?"  Harry looked at Piaget.
\par 
\par "I said drive the damn' car out here for him!" Piaget repeated.  "I've had as much of this as I can stomach!"
\par 
\par Hesitantly, the youth turned toward the garage door.  His feet moved with a dragging slowness.
\par 
\par "See here, Gilbert," Piaget said, "you can't really believe we . . ."
\par 
\par "I believe what I see," Dasein said.
\par 
\par Piaget threw up his hands, tamed away in exasperation.
\par 
\par Dasein listened to the sounds from the garage.  They were subdued in there -- voices, only a few mechanical noises, the whirring buzz of some machine.
\par 
\par A door slammed.  It soun
ded like the door to the truck.  Dasein recognized the grinding of his starter.  The engine caught with its characteristic banging, as drowned immediately in a roaring explosion that sent a blast of flame shooting out the garage door.
\par 
\par Piaget leaped back with an oath.
\par 
\par Dasein ran diagonally past him to look into the garage.  He glimpsed figures rushing out a door at the far end.  His truck stood in the central traffic aisle at the core of a red-orange ball of flame.  As he stared at the truck, a burning
